4.52/5  rDev -3%look: 4.25 | smell: 4.75 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.25 |  overall: 4.5Leaping firmly on the northeast bandwagon, these North Carolina temporarily place themselves in the northeast when putting together this juicy IPA.
The Heist Brewery's Citraquench'l IPA nestles into the glass with a murk and mud appearance that's of semigloss goldenrod. Its creamy white froth holds all those aromatic, succulent perfumes that create an irresisstible ire of creamsickle and herbal sherbet. Juicy and sweet on the tongue, the radiant fructose sweetness of citrus and tropical fruit take on honey dipped proportions, even lightly caramelized at first.
The middle palate bursts with fruit flavor. As the sweetness wavers slightly, the tangy fruits of pink grapefruit, blood orange, pineapple, mango and passionfruit take on the freshest, branch ripe savory succulence possible from hops. Smoothly bitter, the beer's even keel bite carries an herbal, grassy, sassafras-like taste to close.
Medium bodied and trending dry, tart and tantalizing; The beer's juiciness is laced with a bready sweet linger like poundcake. Limited in its bitter value as well as its dryness, its doughy, vegemite center keeps the beer richly of sherbet and finishing only semidry. 1,173 charactersBEERchitect, Feb 03, 2017
