4.6/5  rDev -1.3%look: 4.25 | smell: 4.75 | taste: 4.75 | feel: 4 |  overall: 4.5A: Pours an almost completely opaque super murky burnt orange in color with moderate amounts of active visible carbonation along the edges of the glass and moderate deep golden yellow highlights. The beer has a three finger tall dense foamy beige head that slowly reduces to a medium sized half finger thick cap in the center of the glass surrounded by a large patch of thin film covering the remainder of the surface of the beer and a medium thick ring at the edges of the glass. Significant amounts of lacing are observed.
S: Moderate to strong aromas of citrus/grapefruit (juicy), citrus/orange, tropical/papaya, and tropical/passionfruit hops over the top of light to moderate aromas of biscuit malts.
T: Upfront there are light flavors of biscuit malts with moderate amounts of caramel + grainy sweetness. That is followed by strong flavors of citrus/grapefruit (juicy), citrus/orange, tropical/papaya, and tropical/passionfruit hops which contribute lots of flavor but only a light amount of bitterness which fades away pretty quickly.
M: Slightly heavier than medium bodied with moderate amounts of carbonation. Creamy with a hint of slickness in the finish.
O: Delicious juicy NE style IPA, probably the best one I have had brewed here in NC. Really enjoyable, easy to drink, and a beer that I would be happy to enjoy regularly if I could get my hands on it. It took quite a while to get my hands on this beer and it was well worth the wait and stood up to the hype/demand.
