4.69/5  rDev +0.6%look: 4.25 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.5KevBot89, Sep 30, 2016
4.77/5  rDev +2.4%look: 5 | smell: 4.75 | taste: 4.75 | feel: 4.75 |  overall: 4.75Canned 9/23/16. Consumed 9/29/16.
A: Fits the stylistic bill. This one comes in a super hazy, medium orange-gold color with about a finger of pillowy white head, which slowly dissipates and leaves thick rings of lacing on the glass. It's very turbid and pretty much entirely opaque, with an OJ-like appearance that I rarely get outside of Tree House, Trillium, and a few others. Really really enticing.
S: Lots of citrus and some underlying dank qualities. Up front, I get orange, grapefruit, and loads of sweet melon. Underneath that is a grassy green hop note that kinda reminds me of some west coast IPAs. Overall, it's not an explosively aromatic beer, but as it warms, the aroma does begin to pop more. For a 7.1% beer, it's smells damn good. 
T: Straight citrus juice up front. TONS of orange and a ruby red grapefruit. Hints of more tropical fruits--pineapple and a bit of mango--but mostly a sweet citrus bomb on the initial taste. On the finish, I get a really nice pithy, bitter grapefruit and orange flesh note that combines with the sweet OJ up front to balance it out. Maybe a hint of green hops underneath it all, but definitely not to the extent that I get it on the nose. This is a phenomenal showcase of Citra's flavor profile.
M: Smooth as can be. It's soft while still providing a bit of effervescence on the tongue. In terms of weight, it's medium; not at that creamy level of Tree House IPAs in this range, but it definitely has some heft. There's a wonderful smack of pithy, citrus peel bitterness that hints on the back of the taste and perfectly balances out the sweet citrus flavors.
O: Wow, what an awesome first impression of Heist. After drinking a ton of Tree House, Grimm, and other NE-style beers over the past few weeks, I feel confident in stating that this one stands up to the best. At 7.1%, it's right in my personal ABV sweet spot. It packs a ton of hop flavor while retaining a drinkability that would--for better or for worse--enable me to drink a few of these consecutively. I love the bitter/sweet balance on the finish and the soft, delicate carbonation. If they could amp up the aroma a bit (to bring out some of those sweet citrus notes even more) and add a bit more creaminess to the mouthfeel, this would be up there with Julius, Congress St, etc. for sure. As it stands now, though, it's not far behind!
P.S. As I sip this more, I'm noticing a ton of similarities on both the flavor/aroma profile and the mouthfeel to Trillium's Headroom... Of course, it's thinner and not nearly as intense on the nose, but definitely a Headroom-lite! 2,588 charactersavas, Sep 30, 2016
